Draft article

Introduction

Early March 2026 delivered a brutal reminder of how dependent Australia remains on imported fuel. The sudden escalation of conflict in the Middle East disrupted shipping lanes, drove global crude prices toward US$120 a barrel and squeezed supplies of refined fuels. Within days, Australian wholesale petrol prices leapt by more than 40 cents a litre ￼ and retail prices across the five largest capital cities surged from about 165 cents per litre on 20 February to 219.7 cpl by 11 March ￼. Some regional stations were charging 259.9 cpl for diesel. The consumer watchdog, the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC), warned retailers against price gouging and began publishing weekly fuel‑price updates.

This pump‑price shock coincided with a surge in electric‑vehicle (EV) adoption. Battery‑electric vehicles captured 16.7 % of new‑car sales in December 2025 and 11.8 % in February 2026, when 7,715 EVs were sold ￼; total EV sales in the first two months of 2026 reached 18,543 units ￼. With EVs rapidly gaining ground yet paying no fuel excise, and petrol prices soaring despite no change in tax policy, the question is unavoidable: who is paying for Australia’s transition to electric transport?

This article unpacks the relationship between oil prices and pump prices, outlines how fuel excise works and why it matters, examines the latest EV sales figures and explores emerging proposals for a distance‑based road‑user charge. It shows that without reform, a shrinking pool of petrol drivers will shoulder a growing share of road funding just as they face record fuel costs.

Crude oil v. pump price: understanding the margin

At first glance, the price displayed at the bowser seems to move with the price of crude oil. Indeed, the ACCC notes that the international refined‑fuel benchmark—Singapore Mogas 95 for petrol and Singapore Gasoil 10 ppm for diesel—is the largest component of Australian retail fuel prices ￼. When war in the Middle East erupted in late February 2026, the average Mogas 95 price in Australian dollars jumped by 38 cpl in just three weeks ￼. Wholesale terminal‑gate prices responded immediately, rising from about 152 cpl to 193.7 cpl across the major cities ￼.

Retail prices followed suit but with an extra margin. By 11 March, daily average petrol prices had climbed to 219.7 cpl, nearly 49 cpl higher than three weeks earlier ￼. Diesel rose even faster, hitting 240.2 cpl ￼. These figures underscore two important points. First, the lag between wholesale and retail movements reflects the pricing cycles and inventory practices of retailers. Second, the gap between the imported fuel cost and the pump price includes taxes—fuel excise and Goods and Services Tax (GST)—plus distribution and retail margins. The Australian Institute of Petroleum estimates that roughly 95 % of the wholesale price is determined by the Mogas price and shipping, while only about 5 % covers insurance, terminal costs and wholesale margins ￼.

The ACCC tracks this gap using the gross indicative retail difference, a broad measure of retailer costs and margins. In the December quarter 2025, this margin averaged 17.9 cpl across the five largest cities ￼. Margins differed widely—10.8 cpl in Adelaide and 24.7 cpl in Brisbane ￼—and have tended to expand when crude prices fall, partly explaining why pump prices do not drop as quickly as consumers expect. Even before the March 2026 shock, retail margins were higher than their 2010s average of around 7 cpl, having peaked at 21.3 cpl during the pandemic ￼.

Previous policy interventions have had limited impact on this dynamic. During the March–September 2022 cost‑of‑living crisis, the federal government halved fuel excise from 44.2 cpl to 22.1 cpl ￼. Treasury estimated households would save about $300 ￼, but international supply disruptions meant pump prices remained at record levels ￼. When the full excise was reinstated in late September 2022, it added about 25 cpl (including GST) to the pump price ￼. This experience shows that while excise changes can shift prices at the margin, global oil and refined‑fuel markets are the primary drivers of Australian fuel prices.

Fuel excise and government policy

Fuel excise is a flat sales tax levied by the federal government on petrol and diesel. It is indexed every February and August in line with inflation. In February 2026 the rate increased from 50.8 cpl to 51.6 cpl ￼. Because the Goods and Services Tax is applied on top of the excise, each one‑cent increase in excise adds 1.1 cents to the pump price. Heavy vehicles also pay a separate road‑user charge, while industries such as mining receive fuel tax credits. Importantly, pure electric vehicles (EVs) pay no fuel excise ￼.

The excise was originally introduced in 1929 to finance road building and maintenance, but the link was severed in 1992 ￼. Since then, excise revenue has flowed into general revenue, and only about 57 % of it has been reinvested in land‑transport projects ￼; an even smaller share—less than 6 %—is dedicated to roads ￼. In 2023‑24 the excise generated $15.71 billion and cost the typical household about $1,283 ￼. The Parliamentary Budget Office forecasts that revenue will decline over the coming decade as vehicles become more fuel‑efficient and EVs proliferate ￼.

Calls for another excise cut grew louder as pump prices crossed $2.20 per litre in March 2026. Motoring groups and some opposition politicians argued that halving the excise again would provide immediate relief. However, Treasurer Jim Chalmers emphatically ruled out such a move. At a 4 March press conference he said: “When it comes to fuel excise, that’s not something that we’ve been considering… We’ve got a lot of cost‑of‑living help rolling out in other ways” ￼. Instead, the government has focused on cheaper medicines, income tax cuts and targeted energy rebates. This stance reflects lessons from 2022: cutting the excise is costly to the budget, benefits all motorists regardless of need and does little to moderate prices when international markets are tight ￼.

EV adoption and the shrinking excise base

Although EVs represented just 2 % of Australia’s 21.7 million‑vehicle fleet in 2025 ￼, their market share is growing rapidly. Battery‑electric vehicles comprised 16.7 % of new‑car sales in December 2025 and 11.8 % in February 2026, when the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries recorded 7,715 EVs sold ￼. When broader Electric Vehicle Council data are included, EV sales reached 11,134 vehicles in February, or 11.8 % of the 94,131 new cars sold ￼. Year‑to‑date EV sales for 2026 stand at 18,543, almost double the figure for the same period in 2025 ￼. Plug‑in hybrid sales are also rising, with 5,854 units sold in February compared with 4,871 a year earlier ￼.

At the same time, the average fuel consumption of new combustion vehicles continues to fall: from 11.3 L/100 km in 2005 to 6.9 L/100 km in 2025 ￼. Fuel excise revenue as a share of federal revenue has shrunk from around 11 % in the 1980s to 4 % today ￼. This structural decline means that even if no more EVs were sold, excise receipts would erode. EV uptake accelerates the trend because EV drivers pay nothing at the bowser. As more Australians switch to plug‑in cars to avoid volatile fuel prices and capitalise on government incentives, the funding base for roads contracts further.

Who pays for the EV transition?

Under the current system, petrol and diesel drivers pay for roads through fuel excise, while EV owners contribute nothing. This arrangement was tolerable when EVs were a rounding error, but it becomes inequitable as their market share climbs. Pump prices above $2.20 per litre ￼ mean that internal‑combustion‑engine (ICE) drivers face both record running costs and a substantial tax burden. Meanwhile, EV owners—who tend to be early adopters with higher incomes—receive rebates and fringe‑benefits‑tax exemptions funded from general revenue. As long as the excise revenue is largely treated as general taxation and less than 6 % is reserved for roads ￼, petrol drivers are effectively cross‑subsidising both the road network and wider government programs.

The sense of unfairness is heightened by the government’s messaging. EVs are promoted as a means to reduce household fuel bills and cut emissions, yet the public is rarely told that the cost of maintaining roads—roughly $30 billion annually when state and local governments are included—must still be covered. With EV market share poised to reach 15 % in 2026 and 30 % by the early 2030s, relying on a shrinking group of ICE drivers to fund roads risks a backlash that could slow the transition.

Road‑user charging proposals and policy options

Recognising the looming revenue problem, the federal government and all state treasurers issued a joint statement in September 2025 confirming they are working together to design a national road‑user charge. The statement acknowledges that the rapid development of EV technology “is transforming the outlook for both passenger and freight transport” and that road‑user‑charging reforms should ensure “fair and sustainable funding for road investment and maintenance” without deterring EV uptake. The treasurers committed to phasing in reforms to maximise productivity, climate and consumer benefits.

The Australian Electric Vehicle Association (AEVA) proposes a universal, mass × distance charge, arguing that an EV and a diesel vehicle of identical weight and annual mileage should pay the same amount for road use, but that diesel should incur an additional fee for noise and emissions. The Australian Automotive Dealer Association (AADA) supports a technology‑neutral national scheme that does not discourage hybrids or EVs. Motoring groups such as the New South Wales government have previously floated rates of 2.97 cents/km for EVs and 2.37 cents/km for plug‑in hybrids, which would see an EV driver travelling 10,000 km pay about $300, comparable to the $352 in fuel excise paid by a typical new petrol car ￼.

State‑based road‑user charges introduced in Victoria in 2021 were struck down by the High Court in 2023 because the Constitution grants exclusive power over customs and excise duties to the Commonwealth. That decision forced Victoria to refund the $3.9 million it had collected and underscores the need for a coordinated national scheme. Any reform will need to address privacy concerns, minimise administrative costs and ensure that the charge is applied universally once EVs reach a meaningful share of the fleet. To maintain public support, revenue should be ring‑fenced for transport infrastructure and the rollout of fast‑charging networks ￼.

Conclusion

The Middle‑East conflict of early 2026 has demonstrated how vulnerable Australia is to global fuel shocks. Within weeks, petrol and diesel prices rose by more than 40 cpl, and by mid‑March motorists were paying well over $2.20 per litre ￼. Cutting the fuel excise would provide only fleeting relief and would further erode the already shrinking revenue base that funds our roads. Meanwhile, EVs are surging towards 15 % market share, and vehicles are becoming ever more efficient, meaning that fuel‑excise receipts will continue to fall even without policy changes.

If Australia wants to decarbonise its transport sector while maintaining a safe and efficient road network, it must confront this mismatch between who uses the roads and who pays for them. A distance‑based road‑user charge, applied to all vehicles and introduced once EVs reach significant penetration, offers a fair and sustainable solution. The charge should account for vehicle mass (to reflect road wear) and apply surcharges for noise and emissions so that heavier, dirtier vehicles pay more. Importantly, the revenue should be ring‑fenced for road maintenance and the infrastructure needed for an electrified fleet ￼.

Complementary policies will remain essential. Fuel‑efficiency standards, purchase rebates, fringe‑benefits‑tax exemptions and low‑interest loans can help make EVs affordable until market forces deliver price parity. But as the events of March 2026 show, relying on fuel excise from a dwindling number of petrol drivers is neither fair nor sustainable. With the right mix of reform and incentives, Australia can ensure that the EV transition is funded equitably, that motorists are protected from global fuel shocks, and that the road network is ready for a zero‑emission future.
